# 10. Edge Cases

* One array is empty.
* No common elements.
* All elements are common.
* Common element at the beginning.
* Common element at the end.
* Arrays with negative numbers (if allowed).
* Duplicate common values (handle carefully if the problem permits duplicates).

---

# 11. Interview Explanation (30–60 sec)

"The arrays are sorted, so I use two pointers to traverse them simultaneously. I accumulate separate running sums for both arrays until I encounter a common element. At each common element, I add the larger of the two accumulated sums plus the common value to the answer, then reset both sums. After finishing the traversal, I add the larger remaining suffix sum. Since each element is processed once, the algorithm runs in **O(n + m)** time and **O(1)** extra space."

---

# 12. Key Takeaways

* Sorted arrays enable the two-pointer technique.
* A common element is the only valid switching point.
* Compare segment sums between consecutive common elements.
* Greedy choice is optimal.
* Constant extra space.
* Linear time complexity.

---

# 13. Common Mistakes

* Forgetting to add the larger remaining suffix after the main loop.
* Not resetting `sum1` and `sum2` after a common element.
* Adding both segment sums instead of the maximum.
* Mishandling duplicate common values if present.
* Incorrect pointer movement when elements are equal.

